sections.description: Use Chai with k6 by using the k6chaijs library. Leverage BDD assertions to write tests that scale and are easier to maintain.

sections.title: Assertions
sections.description: Test assertions in k6 using the k6-testing library for both protocol and browser testing

sections.title: Checks
sections.description: Checks are like asserts but differ in that they do not halt the execution, instead, they just store the result of the check, pass or fail, and let the script execution continue.

sections.title: Cookies
sections.description: k6 will transparently manage the receiving, storage and sending of cookies as described above, so that testing of your cookie-based web site or app will just work.

sections.title: Environment variables
sections.description: You can access any environment variables from your k6 script code and use this to supply your VUs with configuration information.

sections.title: Execution context variables
sections.description: k6/execution module provides the capability to get information about the current test execution state inside the test script

sections.title: HTTP debugging
sections.description: Things don't always work as expected. For those cases there is a handy CLI flag, --http-debug, that is good to be aware of.

sections.title: HTTP Requests
sections.description: Define the HTTP requests and methods you want to use. k6 adds tags to the requests, making it easier to filter results. You can customize tags as you wish.

sections.title: Options
sections.description: Options configure test-run behavior. You can set options in multiple locations. Examples for how to use options, and a complete reference.

sections.description: A complete list of all k6 options, with descriptions, defaults, and examples of how to set the option in your script, config files, environment variables, or CLI.

sections.title: Metrics
sections.description: This section covers the important aspect of metrics management in k6. How and what kind of metrics k6 collects automatically (_built-in_ metrics), and what custom metrics you can make k6 collect.

sections.title: Create custom metrics
sections.description: How to build custom k6 metrics for each metric type.

sections.title: Built-in metrics
sections.description: A reference of built-in metrics for different supported protocols.

sections.title: Modules
sections.description: While writing test scripts, it is common to import different modules, or part of modules, for usage throughout the script. In k6, it is possible to import three different kinds of modules.

sections.title: Protocols
sections.description: Out of the box k6 comes with support for a few protocols: HTTP / WebSockets / gRPC / ...

sections.title: gRPC
sections.description: gRPC is a lightweight open-source RPC framework. Starting with k6 v0.29.0, we support unary gRPC requests.

sections.title: HTTP/2
sections.description: When you make HTTP requests in k6 it will automatically upgrade the connection to HTTP/2.0 if the server supports it, just like your web browser would.

sections.title: SSL/TLS
sections.description: By default and without any special configuration, k6 will connect and talk to servers over TLS. You just need to make sure to specify your request URLs with the https scheme.

sections.title: Online Certificate Status Protocol (OCSP)
sections.description: k6 supports OCSP stapling, receiving and parsing a stapled response as part of the TLS connection setup.

sections.title: SSL/TLS client certificates
sections.description: To use client certificates, you specify global that tell k6 how to map a public certificate and private key to the domains they are valid for.

sections.title: SSL/TLS version and ciphers
sections.description: To support testing specific client configurations, you can set a specific version or range of versions of SSL/TLS that should be allowed for a connection.

sections.title: WebSockets
sections.description: Comparing HTTP based tests to WebSocket ones, there are some differences in the structure and inner workings of k6.

sections.title: Scenarios
sections.description: Scenarios allow us to make in-depth configurations to how VUs and iterations are scheduled. This makes it possible to model diverse traffic patterns in load tests.

sections.title: Graceful stop
sections.description: This option is available for all executors except externally-controlled and allows the user to specify a duration to wait before forcefully interrupting them.

sections.title: Open and closed models
sections.description: k6 has two ways to schedule VUs, which can affect test results. k6 implements the open model in its arrival-rate executors.

sections.title: Executors
sections.description: Executors control how k6 schedules VUs and iterations. Choose the executor to model traffic you want to model to test your services

sections.title: Constant arrival rate
sections.description: A fixed number of iterations are started in a specified period of time.

sections.title: Constant VUs
sections.description: A fixed number of VUs execute as many iterations as possible for a specified amount of time.

sections.title: Externally controlled
sections.description: Control and scale execution at runtime via k6 REST API or the CLI.

sections.title: Per VU iterations
sections.description: Each VU executes an exact number of iterations.

sections.title: Ramping arrival rate
sections.description: A variable number of iterations are started in a specified period of time.

sections.title: Ramping VUs
sections.description: A variable number of VUs execute as many iterations as possible for a specified amount of time.

sections.title: Shared iterations
sections.description: A fixed number of iterations are "shared" between a number of VUs, and the test ends once all iterations are executed.

sections.description: The file secret source loads secrets from a plain text file with key=value pairs

sections.title: Mock secret source
sections.description: The mock secret source loads secrets from CLI arguments

sections.title: URL secret source
sections.description: The URL secret source fetches secrets from HTTP endpoints
